re, Scotland":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Sanquhar Castle, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crichton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Creighton   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Creighton","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: habitational name from Crichton, near Edinburgh, first recorded <i>c.</i> 1128 in the form <i>Crectune</i>, in 1287 as <i>Crecton</i>, and in 1360 as <i>Creychtona</i>. The name is probably an early hybrid compound of Old Welsh <i>creic</i> ‘rock’ + Older Scots <i>tun</i> ‘farm, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>). In Ireland and Britain, this form of the name is now found chiefly in northern Ireland; the more usual Scottish forms are   Crichton   and   Crighton  .","Irish: sometimes used for Gaelic <b>Ó Creacháin</b> or <b>Ó Criocháin</b> (see   Crehan  ).","English: habitational name from Creighton in Staffordshire, named with Celtic <i>creig</i> ‘rock’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Crichton - 4th Laird of Sanquhar was born in 1376, in Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Crichton - 3rd Laird of Sanquar, was 28 and his mother, Christian Erskine, was 32. He married Elizabeth Erskine in 1406. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1440, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1376–1440":"1376–1440","1385–1452":"1385–1452","1409–1478":"1409–1478","1433–1478":"1433–1478","1348–1412":"1348–1412","1345–1409":"1345–1409","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","about 1409":"umbes 1409","1348":"1348","1412":"1412","1478":"1478","1433":"1433","1345":"1345","1376":"1376","1452":"1452","AFT. 1409":"pärast 1409","1409":"1409","1406":"1406","Sanquhar Castle, Dumfrie-shire, Scotland":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Castle Sanquhar, Dumfrieshire, Scotland":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Sanquhar Castle, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1376–1440":"1376–1440","1385–1452":"1385–1452","1409–1478":"1409–1478","1433–1478":"1433–1478","1348–1412":"1348–1412","1345–1409":"1345–1409","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","about 1409":"noin 1409","1348":"1348","1412":"1412","1478":"1478","1433":"1433","1345":"1345","1376":"1376","1452":"1452","AFT. 1409":"1409 jälkeen","1409":"1409","1406":"1406","Sanquhar Castle, Dumfrie-shire, Scotland":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Skotlan